  "text": "The complete 1000-year pollen record indicates that pine and birch were the only trees present in the region and that pine has always been overwhelmingly dominant (W. Finsinger, pers. comm., 2011) . Picea pollen is recorded in small amounts but the tree itself cannot have been present nearby, as the pollen quantities during this period are of the same order as at the present day. Moreover, the bedrock of this region produces soil and edaphic conditions which are unsuitable for spruce [CITATION_1] . Therefore, spruce was omitted from the tree volume reconstruction. The negligible charcoal record indicates that there have been no major fires. The vast majority of the charcoal particles recorded were smaller than 40 mm in size and the quantity of these was generally <20 particles cm À2 a",
